	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Okie dokie,to help out the person who wrote the last post Bards can wear pretty much any armor that any melee type player can (including rogues,war,pallys etc) as a newbie you should start out with cloth or if you can afford it leather.(found in your local town,ask someone where to buy it they will tell ya) as you progress second armor suit will be banded.Armor crafters can make this and usually charge 1pp per AC, the breastplate is 15 Armor class so would cost 15 platinum points(pp). Hold banded for as long as you can. I've seen several bards that move up to bronze armor (2pp per 1 ac) which is a little higher armor class but I STRONGLY disagree with doing this. Bronze weighs way too much for a bard to wear. Unless you have put all your distributive points you got when you created your character, on strength then a full suit of bronze will well over encumber you. Being a bard  this isn't such a good descision.Encumberance lowers your agility and your dexterity. Two of the key parts of the bard. You take a bards speed away not much he can do. Well anyways. Hold banded until you can get plate (or if you can find some magical armor that you can afford) plate mail costs 10pp per ac usually. You should be well in your 20s or 30s by now. Then when you can afford it you can buy lambent. Blue armor that has stats that help a bard out fairly well. Not a set amount on these. Lambent breastplate(20 AC +25 health and some other stuff) cost me 700pp. That's pretty much it for armor. You can prolly find some better after lambent just maybe but most level 50+ bards I have seen still wear lambent.<BR>
<BR>
Instruments.Instruments inhance your abilities if the song is based on that instrument. At lower level they are not really required unless you are traveling which a drum will increase your selos quite a bit. But to be on the safe side I would get my instruments early if I could afford them (again they are not nessessary). that way you can start getting your skills up sooner and you won't miss notes as much.<BR>
<BR>
Weapons. Well bards can use most weps that a melee class can use as well.Shords.Maces.Axes. We just can't use 2 handed weapons. To start out I would prolly say get you a 1hs wep of some sort and progress up as you get the money too. Weps are a key role at an early level but lessin at higher levels.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Onto next person.<BR>
The reason it is harder to solo at higher levels is because I guess EQ staff was trying to be realistic. Us players are limited to our dmg speed and such. It all depends on your equipment and skills. The non player characters(beasts and such) are also limited to their skills, just at a higher rate all depending on the monster. Just wouldn't be realistic at all if you could walk up to a Hill Giant(10 or more times the size of a ogre) and face him head to toe and both be at the same level. That's why it takes groups. Same for dragons. What person could honestly face a dragon face to face? I myself can't face some greens. I'm level 35 and can't stand toe to toe with most level 25s cause they hit in the 50s. Which is average for a creature at level 25. I only hit in the 20s and 30s though. Of course I have 2 weps and a low delay so I hit a whole lot quicker but then again they have higher Health so I have to fear kite them.<BR>
<BR>
The reason bards can't kick is because we are not consider tanks. All tanks(classes that are mean't the get in the battle and fight and pretty much nothing else) have kick and double attack. We don't get either. Fortunatly we don't need either cause we have our songs,our art, our life......<BR>
<BR>
Isthamae Cantante<BR>
Bard of the 35th missed note<BR>
Tholuxe paels<BR>
Leader of &quot;Scar of the Dragon&quot;
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
