	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				    In response to the question about bards' fighting at later levels...<BR>
    I'm on 27, which admittedly doesn't fit the &quot;later&quot; qualifier, but from my experience so far, and from the descriptions of the higher level songs, I think that Bards are indeed good at fighting at later levels.<BR>
    At 27, and at every level up until now, I have been able to easily solo any ordinary blue mob, and occasionally a white (haven't taken on a white con since level 25).  And this is only with melee.  On occasion, if I get in over my head (i.e. two or more mobs with one being pretty near my level), I'll just heal kite for a bit.  Slap on selo's and run for a moment, and then switch to your lute and twist selo's and the healing song.  At my level I get back 11hp per tick while doing this, plus i can easily outrun any enemies that i've fought (cyclopses and such are probably different).  Do this for two or three minutes, just making wide circles, and you'll fill up half of your life and be ready to take them on again.<BR>
    There are also other ways to fight, especially starting at level 26.  I just bought my level 24, 25, 26, and 27 songs today, so I haven't tried these strategies out yet, but I assume they will work well enough.<BR>
    First there is fear kiting.  The level 26 song is an area of effect fear song.  I'm sure this would work best with only one enemy, but as long as things didn't get out of hand it would probably keep you safe if there were two or three.  The strategy is simple:  snare, fear.  In that order.  Repeat.  You could add in a whistling warsong or a DoT, but only having the two gives you a chance to re-sing a song if it is resisted, or if you get several wrong notes in a row.  While the enemy is running--or rather walking--just follow along and hack away.  If you're in an area where there are lots of aggroing mobs nearby, this method would probably actually be much better than necro fear kiting, as you can cancel the song and have it end in a fairly short time.<BR>
    Secondly, there's the charming strategy.  At level 27 you get a song (I rarely pay attention to the names of songs, just the effect.  Look it up in the spells section) that charms enemies.  From my understanding its duration is variable, depending in part upon your charisma.  So, get the mask of deception.  +13 cha.  Good stuff, and pretty easy to get since its no drop and brd/rog only.  Just find an enemy, probably a blue so that it has a good chance of sticking, and charm it.  Keep the song cycling.  Find another enemy and have your &quot;pet&quot; attack.  Hopefully your pet will kill it, in which case you'll get that exp, and your pet will be low on life.  Let the charm run out and squish your pet, for double exp.  Repeat.<BR>
    There are also the many DoTs available to bards.  I havent experimented with these too much because I suspect that they would require more concentration, or at least more though, to pull off.  I'm the lazy type, and proud of it.  But I'm sure you can find posts of how to DoT solo either somewhere else on this MB or else in one of the DoT song message boards.  Good hunting!
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
